date
The date command displays the current system date, time, and time zone configuration.

Bash
date
Sample Output: Sat Jun 27 23:01:25 +06 2026

Formatting Output
You can customize how date formats its output by using a plus sign (+) followed by format specifiers:

Display only the date (YYYY-MM-DD):

Bash
date +%F
Display standard clock time (HH:MM:SS):

Bash
date +%T
Custom Layouts: You can combine specific layout components (like %Y for year, %m for month, %d for day) with regular text:

Bash
date +"Today is %Y-%m-%d"
Redirection with date
You can use the redirection operators (> and >>) to log timestamps to text files:

Overwrite (>): Replaces the target file's contents entirely with the current timestamp. If the file doesn't exist, it creates it.

Bash
date > log.txt
Append (>>): Adds the current timestamp as a new line at the very bottom of the file without altering existing data. Ideal for history logging.

Bash
date >> log.txt